    "trend_analysis": "The schedule has consistently added more non-banned alternatives each year. Proposed ban chemicals remain listed but are being flanked by clean alternatives. Marssonina Leaf Blotch is the emerging new disease pressure. The app should flag the trend: every year, ban-list chemicals are used less; transition farmers NOW to build clean spray habits."
  },
  "washington_state_learnings": {
    "source": "WSU Extension Spokane County C041, revised 2023/2024",
    "key_principles_to_adopt": [
      {
        "principle": "Identify before you spray",
        "wsu_text": "Do not apply pesticides until a specific insect or disease has been positively identified",
        "app_feature": "Add symptom identification flow in onboarding. Show photo-based disease ID guide. Ask: what are you seeing on your trees? before recommending a spray."
      },
      {
        "principle": "Rotate chemical classes",
        "wsu_text": "Vary products during the season and in following seasons to minimize pest resistance",
        "app_feature": "Track spray log and detect if farmer is repeating same active ingredient class. Alert: you have used Tebuconazole 3 times — consider switching to a different fungicide class."
      },
      {
        "principle": "Pollinator protection at bloom",
        "wsu_text": "Apply in the evening after bees have stopped foraging",
        "app_feature": "During Bloom stage (Stage 3 petal fall), add timing advisory: spray insecticides only after 6pm."
      },
      {
        "principle": "Weather-triggered reapplication",
        "wsu_text": "Reapply after brief, heavy rainfall or showers of longer duration",
        "app_feature": "Already in HP schedule rules — WSU confirms this. Implement rain_repeat rule as high priority."
      },
      {
        "principle": "Pheromone traps for early detection",
        "wsu_text": "Methyl eugenol pheromone trap may be installed to check fruit fly attack",
        "app_feature": "Phase 2 feature: prompt farmer to set traps at season start. Farmer reports trap catches → app adjusts insecticide recommendation timing."
      },
      {
        "principle": "Cultural control first",
        "wsu_text": "Remove infested apples from tree, seal in bags, leave in sun to kill larvae",
        "app_feature": "Add cultural control tips alongside every chemical recommendation. Reduces dependency on chemicals, reduces cost, improves IPM profile."
      }
    ],
    "key_differences_hp_vs_washington": [
      "Washington focuses on Codling Moth, Apple Maggot, Brown Marmorated Stink Bug — these are less prevalent in HP",
      "HP focuses on San Jose Scale, Mites, Woolly Apple Aphid — different pest complex",
      "Washington uses no-spray defaults for many diseases (cultural management only) — HP is more chemical-intensive",
      "Washington schedule is homeowner-focused (trees under 10ft) — HP is commercial orchard scale",
      "Washington has legal requirement to control certain pests — HP is voluntary advisory"
    ]
  },
